    <!-- FAQs -->
    <section id="faqs" class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="space-y-4">
        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How does Antigua compare to other Caribbean CBI programs?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 text-sm">
            Antigua offers the best value for families of 4+ (same $100,000 NDF as singles). St. Kitts has the
            "Platinum Standard" reputation but costs more. Dominica is cheapest for singles/couples. Grenada
            uniquely offers US E-2 Treaty access. Antigua's 5-day/5-year residency requirement is the most minimal.
            Choose based on: family size, US plans, budget, and how much you value program prestige.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I include adult children?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 text-sm">
            Yes, dependent children up to age 30 can be included if they're financially dependent and unmarried.
            Children 18-30 must be enrolled in higher education or show financial dependency. This is more generous
            than some programs that cap at 25. Adult children 31+ cannot be included as dependents.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What happens after 5 years with the real estate option?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 text-sm">
            After the 5-year holding period, you can sell the property. However, if you sell to another CBI
            applicant (who uses it for their own application), the new buyer only needs to hold for 5 years—this
            can facilitate resale. You keep your citizenship regardless of whether you sell. Government fees paid
            are non-refundable.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I have to pay taxes in Antigua?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 text-sm">
            Antigua has no income tax, capital gains tax, wealth tax, or inheritance tax. There's also no tax
            on worldwide income. If you establish tax residency (183+ days/year), you still won't pay these taxes.
            However, most CBI holders don't establish tax residency—they remain tax resident in their primary
            country. Consult a tax professional about your specific situation.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I add family members after initial approval?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 text-sm">
            Yes, you can add dependents after citizenship is granted: newborn children automatically qualify;
            new spouse or other dependents require a new application with additional fees. Adding dependents later
            costs more than including them in the initial application, so include everyone eligible from the start
            if possible.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-white border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-6">
          <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What's the 5-day residency requirement exactly?</h3>
          <p class="text-neutral-700 text-sm">
            Within the first 5 years of citizenship, you must spend a cumulative minimum of 5 days physically
            present in Antigua and Barbuda. This can be one trip or spread across multiple visits. It's the most
            minimal residency requirement among Caribbean CBI programs (St. Kitts has none). Failure to comply
            before passport renewal could create complications—plan a vacation to fulfill it.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Final Verdict -->
    <section id="verdict" class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

      <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 mb-6">
        <p class="text-primary-900 mb-4">
          Antigua and Barbuda's CBI program stands out for family-friendly pricing—a family of 4 pays the same
          $100,000 NDF contribution as a single applicant. This makes it the most cost-effective Caribbean option
          for families with multiple children. The extended family inclusion (parents, grandparents, siblings) is
          also more generous than competitors.
        </p>
        <p class="text-primary-900 mb-4">
          The 5-day residency requirement over 5 years is minimal but noteworthy—it's less than a week total. With
          150+ visa-free countries including the UK and Schengen Area, the passport provides solid travel freedom.
          The main gap versus Grenada is the lack of US E-2 Treaty access—if US relocation is a goal, Grenada is
          the only Caribbean option.
        </p>
        <p class="text-primary-900">
          Healthcare is basic on the islands—international insurance with evacuation coverage is mandatory for
          anyone spending time there. Most CBI holders visit occasionally while maintaining residence elsewhere,
          making this less of a concern for typical applicants.
